{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] --> | name = Hollywood | title_orig = | translator = | image = File:HollywoodVidal.jpg | caption = Cover of the first edition | author = [[Gore Vidal]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = [[Narratives of Empire]] | genre = [[Historical novel]] | publisher = [[Random House]] | release_date = 1990 | english_release_date = | media_type = Print ([[Hardback]] & [[Paperback]]) | pages = 448pp | isbn = 0-375-70875-8 | congress = PS3543.I26 H65 2000 | oclc = 50253286 | preceded_by = [[Empire (Vidal novel)|Empire]] | followed_by = [[Washington, D.C. (novel)|Washington, D.C.]] }} '''''Hollywood''''' is the fifth [[historical novel]] in [[Gore Vidal]]'s ''[[Narratives of Empire]]'' series. Published in 1990, it brings back the fictional Caroline Sanford, Blaise Sanford and James Burden Day and the real [[Theodore Roosevelt]] and [[William Randolph Hearst]] from ''[[Empire (1987 novel)|Empire]]'' (the fourth novel in the series). Events are seen through the eyes of the Sanfords, Day, and the historical [[Jess Smith]], a member of the [[Ohio Gang]].
Historical characters introduced in this novel include [[Woodrow Wilson]], [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] and [[Warren G. Harding]], as well early [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] figures such as [[Charlie Chaplin]], [[Marion Davies]], [[Elinor Glyn]], [[Mabel Normand]], and [[William Desmond Taylor]], whose 1922 murder Vidal presents in fictionalized form.
In the novel, Hearst and Caroline separately enter the movie business. Caroline becomes both a producer and, using a pseudonym, also performs as an actress. All this takes place while Wilson [[American entry into World War I|enters]] the [[United States]] into [[World War I]] and battles over the [[League of Nations]], and Harding's subsequent attempts to return the country to "Normalcy". {{Clear}} {{American-chronicle}} {{Gore Vidal}}
